s Leland Saito traces these two parallel trends through specific construction projects and the backlash they provoked. He uses these events to theorize the past and present processes of racial formation and the racialization of place, drawing new insights on the relationships between race, place, and policy. Saito brings to bear the importance of historical events on contemporary processes of gentrification and integrates the fluidity of racial categories into his analysis. He explores these forces in action, as buyers and entrepreneurs meet in the real estate marketplace, carrying with them a fraught history of exclusion and vast disparities in wealth among racial groups.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aCentral business districtszCaliforniazLos Angeles. 0aCity planningzCaliforniazLos Angeles. 0aGentrificationzCaliforniazLos Angeles. 0aMinoritieszCaliforniazLos Angeles. 0aUrban renewalzCaliforniazLos Angeles. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Discrimination & Race Relations.2bisacsh  aCommunity Benefits Agreements.  aGentrification.  aconvention centers.  agrowth coalitions.  aracial formation.  aracial wealth gap.  aracial-spatial formation.  aracialization of place.  asocial justice coalitions.  asports arenas.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishz978311099389908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022z9783110994810oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology 2022 Englishz978311099455108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology 2022z9783110994520oZDB-23-DSL08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z97831107664860 cprintz978150363239440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/97815036325